Assignment:

    - Add parallelism to p6 (coroutines are multiplexed over OS threads)
    - A change in the channel API makes it possible to reliably delete
      channels.
    - Add 2 new functions as discussed in class:
        - stop(), never returns and terminates the calling coroutine
        - yield(), called by a coroutine to allow another ready
          coroutine to run.
    - remove "again". It was in p6 to help you understand the difference
      between setjmp/longjmp and try/catch/throw.
    - A program terminates when either:
       - go_main returns
       - "exit" is called

Source of parallelism:

     We will get parallelism from OS threads; created in main using the
     standard C++ library thread creation mechanism.

     Any changes you make to main.cc will be replaced when you push your code

   
Warnings:
    - Many standard synchronization primitives (e.g. std::mutex)
      are unable to handle releasing a lock from a different thread.
    - Think about blocking a thread vs. block a coroutine
    - Think about floating point


